('Cricket Fast Bowling Run-Up Drill',
 'quads', array['glutes','hamstrings','core','calves'], array['quads','glutes','hamstrings'],
 'sport_specific', 'locomotion', array['bodyweight'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Mark a bowling crease. From a measured run-up (typically 20-30m for fast bowlers), accelerate through the crease focusing on the bound stride (the penultimate stride before delivery). Perform 8-10 run-up approaches without actually bowling. Focus on gathering momentum into the crease.',
 'Stopping the run-up before the crease (must continue through the delivery stride), inconsistent step count (mark your starting point precisely — even one extra stride changes the body position at delivery).',
 'cricket',
 array['The bound: the second-to-last stride is a long, powerful bound that generates the energy transferred into the delivery','Consistent step count: count every run-up repetition — elite fast bowlers know their exact run-up to the step','Heel-to-toe loading in the bound: the heel hits first, transfers to the toe — this is the launch pad for the bowling action','Video your run-up: the run-up mechanics are invisible to the bowler — video analysis reveals inconsistencies that feel correct'],
 array['Full Fast Bowling Action with Ball','Run-Up with Load Monitoring'],
 array['Short Run-Up Practice (5 Steps)','Walk-In Bowling Action'],
 array['cricket','fast_bowling','run_up','speed','sports_specific'],
 array['stress_fractures_lower_limb','acute_lower_back_injury'],
 'explosive', 'sagittal', false, 3, 8, null, 60, true),

('Fast Bowling Back Strength (Lumbar Extension)',
 'erectors', array['multifidus','QL','glutes'], array['erectors','glutes'],
 'sport_specific', 'extension', array['bodyweight','resistance_bands'], 'intermediate', false,
 'The fast bowling action places extreme lumbar extension stress on the spine (particularly in mixed-action and side-on bowlers). Targeted lower back strengthening is essential for injury prevention. Perform: Bird Dog × 15 each side → Back Extension × 15 → Superman Hold × 30 seconds × 3. This is a circuit.',
 'Training these exercises in isolation and not monitoring bowling load alongside the gym work (the combination of high bowling volume AND heavy gym back work creates the overload that causes spondylolysis).',
 'cricket',
 array['Fast bowlers have the highest incidence of lumbar stress fracture (spondylolysis) of any sport: structured back strengthening reduces this risk significantly','The bird dog: the foundation of lumbar stability — builds the multifidus strength specific to protecting the spine in the bowling action','Never train back exercises and high bowling volume on the same day: recovery sequencing is as important as the exercise selection','Bowling action type matters: mixed-action and front-on bowlers have significantly different spinal loading patterns — individualized programs are required'],
 array['Weighted Back Extension','Deadlift as Lumbar Strengthening'],
 array['Gentle Bird Dog','Back Extension Bodyweight'],
 array['cricket','fast_bowling','injury_prevention','lumbar','spondylolysis_prevention'],
 array['acute_spondylolysis','acute_lower_back_injury','stress_fracture_lumbar'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', false, 3, 15, null, 45, true),

('Cricket Batting Rotational Power',
 'obliques', array['glutes','erectors','lats','forearms'], array['obliques','glutes','erectors'],
 'sport_specific', 'rotation', array['medicine_ball','cable_machine'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Simulate the batting drive rotation pattern: stand in batting stance (side-on to target), hold a medicine ball or cable handle at the rear hip. Rotate explosively through the swing arc — hips lead, shoulder follows, arms extend. Drive the ball/handle toward the target.',
 'Arms rotating before the hips (the kinetic chain must be: ground → hips → core → shoulder → arms — arm-dominated rotation produces 30% less power than hip-driven rotation), swinging with a bent front knee (the front leg is the axis of the batting rotation).',
 'cricket',
 array['Hips lead: the batting stroke begins with the front hip pulling toward the ball — the arms are the last link in the chain','Front leg as axis: the drive rotation pivots around a straight front leg — bending it kills the rotation efficiency','Drive through the contact point: the bat should be accelerating through the ball''s contact zone, not decelerating toward it','Bilateral training: bat both left and right-handed in gym training to prevent the extreme rotational asymmetry that causes lower back and shoulder injuries over years of one-sided sport'],
 array['Batting Rotation with Resistance Band','Batting Power Med Ball Slam'],
 array['Seated Rotation with Medicine Ball','Simple Hip Rotation'],
 array['cricket','batting','rotational_power','sports_specific','core'],
 array['acute_lower_back_injury','shoulder_injuries_acute','rib_stress_fractures'],
 'explosive', 'transverse', true, 4, 10, null, 60, true),

('Cricket Wicketkeeper Squat Endurance',
 'quads', array['glutes','hamstrings','core','calves'], array['quads','glutes','hamstrings'],
 'sport_specific', 'squat', array['bodyweight'], 'intermediate', true,
 'From the wicketkeeper stance (deep squat, heels flat or slightly raised, hands in catching position). Hold for 10 seconds. Rise to standing for 5 seconds. Repeat for 20-30 repetitions, simulating an over of wicketkeeping. Progress to holding weighted gloves.',
 'Heels lifting (wicketkeepers must maintain a flat-footed squat for stability and reach — ankle dorsiflexion is the limiting factor and must be addressed), letting the knees collapse inward when fatigued.',
 'cricket',
 array['The wicketkeeper stance is one of the most physically demanding athletic positions: up to 600+ squats per day in a Test match over 6 hours of field time','Flat feet: the most important wicketkeeper mobility goal — ankle dorsiflexion training enables this foot position in the deep squat','Hands ready: the catching hands must be in the ready position throughout — this is a full-body task, not just a leg exercise','Calf endurance matters: by session 3 of a Test match, calf fatigue is the primary performance limiter for most wicketkeepers'],
 array['Wicketkeeper Squat with Ball Drills','Full Session Wicketkeeper Simulation'],
 array['Goblet Squat Hold','Box Squat with Hold'],
 array['cricket','wicketkeeping','squat_endurance','sports_specific','hip_mobility'],
 array['knee_injuries_acute','ankle_injuries_acute'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', false, 4, 20, null, 60, true),

('Cricket Throwing Arm Shoulder Program',
 'deltoids', array['rotator_cuff','rhomboids','serratus','triceps'], array['deltoids','rotator_cuff'],
 'sport_specific', 'pull', array['resistance_bands','dumbbells'], 'intermediate', false,
 'A complete cricket throwing shoulder maintenance circuit: Band External Rotation (15 × 3) → Prone Y-T-W (12 × 3) → Sleeper Stretch (60s × 3) → Cross-body Stretch (45s × 3) → Serratus Wall Slide (12 × 3). Performed before and after each throwing session.',
 'Skipping this program when pressed for time (shoulder injuries in cricket are cumulative — the program must be consistent, not occasional), using too much resistance in the external rotation (the shoulder is not built for heavy external rotation loads).',
 'cricket',
 array['The throwing shoulder in cricket is under enormous rotational stress: up to 7000° of rotation per second during the throw','External rotation is the decelerator: the posterior rotator cuff decelerates the arm after ball release — this is where cricket injuries occur, not at ball release','Sleeper stretch after every training: this maintains internal rotation range that is progressively lost with repeated throwing — loss of internal rotation is the #1 predictor of rotator cuff injury in throwing athletes','Pre-season screening: get a bilateral shoulder strength and range test at the start of every season — asymmetries greater than 10% need correction before full bowling loads begin'],
 array['Full Overhead Throwing Load Program','Advanced Rotator Cuff Progression'],
 array['Band External Rotation Only','Gentle Shoulder Mobility'],
 array['cricket','shoulder_health','rotator_cuff','throwing','injury_prevention'],
 array['rotator_cuff_tears_acute','shoulder_instability_severe'],
 'pull', 'transverse', true, 3, 15, null, 30, true),

('Cricket Fielding Dive and Recovery',
 'core', array['glutes','shoulder','quads','hip_flexors'], array['core','glutes','shoulder'],
 'sport_specific', 'explosive', array['yoga_mat','bodyweight'], 'intermediate', true,
 'From an athletic stance, take 2-3 sprint steps toward a ball position. Perform a controlled dive (hands first, slide on hip/thigh), collect a simulated ball, rise to one knee, throw position. Repeat 6-8 reps each side.',
 'Landing on the knees instead of sliding on the hip and thigh (knees-first diving creates MCL and patella injuries — the correct landing surface is the front of the hip and thigh), diving with arms not outstretched (hands must reach for the ball position).',
 'cricket',
 array['Hip-thigh landing: the dive lands on the outside of the hip and thigh simultaneously — never the knee','Hands ahead of the body: the hands reach for where the ball will be, not where it is — anticipation is the athletic skill','Rise quickly: the recovery from the dive to throwing position must be fast — practice the rise as many times as the dive itself','This drill has the second-highest injury rate in cricket training: always warm up fully before diving practice and use a mat until the technique is proficient on grass'],
 array['Full Fielding Circuit with Sprints','Competition-Speed Fielding Drill'],
 array['Controlled Lateral Dive onto Mat','Slow Dive Practice'],
 array['cricket','fielding','diving','agility','sports_specific'],
 array['shoulder_injuries_acute','hip_injuries_acute','wrist_injuries'],
 'explosive', 'multi', true, 4, 6, null, 90, true),

('Cricket Crease Footwork Ladder',
 'calves', array['quads','glutes','hip_flexors'], array['calves','quads'],
 'sport_specific', 'locomotion', array['agility_ladder','bodyweight'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Using an agility ladder set along the batting crease. Practice: 1) Batting shuffle (feet moving in the crease while watching for the ball). 2) Front-foot drive footwork. 3) Back-foot defence footwork. 4) Sweep shot footwork. Each pattern 3 × 6 repetitions.',
 'Looking down at the ladder (must maintain eyes forward as if tracking a ball — watching the feet is a fatal habit in batting), rushing through the footwork before the pattern is learned at slow speed.',
 'cricket',
 array['Eyes forward throughout: in batting, the eyes must track the ball from the bowler''s hand, not watch the feet — ladder drills done with eyes-forward develop the correct pattern','Each shot type has a specific footwork pattern: the front foot drive moves forward and across, the back-foot defence steps back and across — practice each distinctly','Weight through the balls of the feet: the batting stance requires readiness to move in any direction — flat-footed stances cause late reactions','The crease area ladders use an agility ladder placed along the batting crease length — both sides of the crease are practiced'],
 array['Batting Footwork at Competition Speed','Batting Footwork with Ball Feed'],
 array['Slow Batting Footwork Practice','Shadow Batting Without Ladder'],
 array['cricket','batting','footwork','agility','sports_specific'],
 array['ankle_injuries_acute','knee_injuries_acute'],
 'explosive', 'multi', false, 3, 6, null, 45, true),

('Cricket Pace Bowling Shoulder Warm-Up',
 'deltoids', array['rotator_cuff','traps','serratus'], array['deltoids','rotator_cuff'],
 'sport_specific', 'multi_joint', array['resistance_bands'], 'beginner', false,
 'Pre-bowling 10-minute shoulder preparation sequence: 1) Arm circles (10 forward, 10 back). 2) Band external rotation × 15. 3) Band internal rotation × 15. 4) Band face pull × 15. 5) Cross-body stretch 45s. 6) Sleeper stretch 45s. 7) 10 easy underarm throws building to full arm speed over 20 throws.',
 'Skipping this warm-up before bowling (the incidence of shoulder injury in bowling is strongly correlated with inadequate warm-up, particularly at the start of sessions and on cold days), warming up only the arm without warming up the hips and core (the entire kinetic chain participates in the bowling action).',
 'cricket',
 array['Progressive intensity: the 20 gradual throws at the end are as important as the exercises — the arm needs to feel ball-release before full effort bowling','Cold weather: double the warm-up duration on cold days. The rotator cuff muscles are metabolically demanding tissues and lose power rapidly in the cold.','The shoulder complex: the glenohumeral (ball and socket) AND the scapular stabilizers (serratus, rhomboids, lower traps) must all be warm — the band exercises address both','This warm-up is non-negotiable for fast bowlers: start your bowling career with this habit and maintain it for life'],
 array['Full Pre-Bowling Warm-Up Protocol','Multi-Sport Throwing Warm-Up'],
 array['Simple Arm Swing Warm-Up','Static Shoulder Stretch Only'],
 array['cricket','warm_up','shoulder','fast_bowling','injury_prevention'],
 array['acute_shoulder_injuries','rotator_cuff_tears_acute'],
 'mixed', 'multi', false, 1, null, 600, null, true),

('Cricket Sprint Between Wickets',
 'quads', array['hamstrings','calves','glutes'], array['quads','hamstrings','calves'],
 'sport_specific', 'locomotion', array['bodyweight'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Set up two cones 17.68m apart (the exact distance between cricket wickets). Sprint from one to the other, turn at the crease, and sprint back. Complete 3 sets of 5 shuttles with 90-second recovery. Focus on the turning technique (pivot on the toe, not the heel).',
 'Decelerating before the crease line (in a real run, the bat is grounded past the crease — practice grounding a bat in training), turning with a flat-foot pivot instead of a toe-pivot (toe-pivot is faster and allows a more explosive push-off).',
 'cricket',
 array['17.68m is the precise between-wicket distance: training at the exact distance develops the specific sprint-deceleration-turn-reaccelerate pattern used in the game','Toe pivot turn: the foot of the turn leg pivots on the toe, allowing the body to rotate quickly — practice slow then fast','Bat grounding: in competitive play, the bat must touch the ground past the crease line before the ball reaches — practice this habit in sprint drills','Call and response: in a real match, between-wickets communication is verbal — train with a partner and include the verbal call (''Yes!'', ''No!'', ''Wait!'') in the drill'],
 array['Between-Wicket Sprint with Calling','Match Simulation Running Between Wickets'],
 array['Simple 20m Sprint','Acceleration Drill 10m'],
 array['cricket','batting','running_between_wickets','speed','sports_specific'],
 array['hamstring_strain_recent','stress_fractures_lower_limb'],
 'explosive', 'sagittal', false, 3, 5, null, 90, true),

('Cricket Core Anti-Rotation for Batting',
 'obliques', array['core','erectors'], array['obliques','core'],
 'sport_specific', 'isometric', array['cable_machine','resistance_bands'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Pallof Press with cricket batting stance: stand in batting stance (sideways to the cable), hold the cable at chest height. Press forward to full extension and hold 2 seconds. Return. This trains the core''s ability to resist rotation — critical for stable batting technique. 3 × 12 each side.',
 'Standing facing the cable instead of sideways (the exercise targets anti-rotation in the batting stance — the sideways position is deliberate), not fully extending the arms (the moment of maximum challenge is at full extension).',
 'cricket',
 array['Batting stance sideways: both the lead-on and square-on batting stance positions are worth practicing — they create different anti-rotation demands','The Pallof press is the safest core exercise for cricketers: it builds the stiffness required for a stable batting platform without the rotational forces that cause lumbar injury','Full extension hold: the 2-second hold at full extension is where the core works hardest — don''t rush this','Anti-rotation must balance rotation: use the rotational power exercises (medicine ball rotations) alongside the anti-rotation exercises (Pallof press) for a complete cricket core program'],
 array['Batting Stance Pallof Press Heavy','Pallof Press with Batting Movement'],
 array['Simple Pallof Press Neutral Stance','Standing Isometric Core Hold'],
 array['cricket','core','anti_rotation','batting','injury_prevention'],
 array['acute_lower_back_injury','shoulder_injuries_acute'],
 'isometric', 'transverse', true, 3, 12, null, 45, true),

('Spin Bowling Wrist Strength',
 'forearms', array['wrist_flexors','finger_flexors','brachioradialis'], array['forearms'],
 'sport_specific', 'isolation', array['resistance_bands','grip_trainer'], 'beginner', false,
 'A wrist and finger strengthening circuit for spin bowlers: 1) Wrist curl 3 × 20. 2) Wrist extension 3 × 20. 3) Finger flexion with resistance band 3 × 20. 4) Supination with light dumbbell 3 × 15 each. 5) Pronation with light dumbbell 3 × 15 each. Perform twice weekly.',
 'Training only the wrist flexors (the extensors and the supination/pronation muscles are equally important for spin bowling control and injury prevention), using too much resistance (wrist and finger training is a high-rep, low-resistance activity).',
 'cricket',
 array['The spin bowler''s wrist: off-spin, leg-spin, and finger-spin all create different wrist and finger demands — identify which muscles your specific action stresses most','Supination for leg-spin: the leg-spinner''s delivery involves wrist supination at ball release — this is a specific movement that must be trained directly','Finger tip strength: press the tips of all five fingers against a flat surface and hold for 5 seconds — this replicates the grip strength needed to rip a leg-break','Wrist injuries are career-ending in spin bowling: prevention through strengthening is far more effective than rehabilitation'],
 array['Advanced Wrist Strength Progression','Full Spin Bowling Grip Protocol'],
 array['Simple Wrist Circles','Tennis Ball Squeeze'],
 array['cricket','spin_bowling','wrist_strength','forearms','injury_prevention'],
 array['wrist_injuries_acute','carpal_tunnel_severe','finger_injuries'],
