('Cricket Fielding Reaction Sprint',
 'quads', array['hamstrings','glutes','calves'], array['quads','hamstrings'],
 'sport_specific', 'explosive', array['bodyweight'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Set up 4 cones in a 10m square. Partner calls a direction (forward, back, left, right) from behind. React to the call and sprint to that cone. Touch the cone and return to center. Repeat for 8-10 reactions with full recovery between sets.',
 'Anticipating the direction before the call (defeats the reactive element), being flat-footed in the ready position (must be on the balls of the feet in an athletic stance), not completing the full sprint to the cone (short-cutting reduces the training benefit).',
 'cricket',
 array['Athletic ready position: slightly bent knees, weight on balls of feet, eyes forward — this is the fielding stance that enables quick reactions','Reaction time is trainable: the key is the stimulus-to-movement time (reaction time) AND the acceleration phase — both are developed in this drill','Touch the cone: physical contact with the cone confirms a complete sprint — habit of completing the full sprint transfers to competition behavior','The best fielders have fast reactions AND fast first steps: this drill combines both in one exercise'],
 array['Reaction Sprint with Multiple Simultaneous Stimuli','Fielding Reaction Sprint with Ball Pickup'],
 array['Predetermined Direction Sprint','Cone Touch Sprint Basic'],
 array['cricket','fielding','reaction_time','agility','sports_specific'],
 array['hamstring_strain_recent','ankle_injuries_acute'],
 'explosive', 'multi', false, 4, 8, null, 90, true),

('Cricket Seam Bowling Hip Drive',
 'glutes', array['hamstrings','hip_flexors','core'], array['glutes','hamstrings'],
 'sport_specific', 'explosive', array['bodyweight','resistance_bands'], 'intermediate', true,
 'From a side-on bowling stance (non-bowling arm raised, front hip forward). Explosively drive the front hip through toward the target (this is the ''hip leading'' phase of the bowling action). Return to start. Perform with band resistance around the waist. 3 × 12 each side.',
 'Driving with the arm instead of the hip (in seam bowling, the hip drives through first — the arm follows the hip. Arm-dominant bowling loses 15-20% of potential delivery speed), not completing the full range of hip drive.',
 'cricket',
 array['Hips before arms: say it before every set. The hip drives through — the ball follows the hip.','The front hip is the engine of fast bowling: hip extension speed is the single best predictor of bowling pace among young fast bowlers','Band resistance version: the band around the waist creates resistance to the forward hip drive — this trains the exact movement against a load that is impossible to achieve with free weights','This exercise, done 3 × 12 before bowling sessions, increases pace by developing the hip drive pattern that many bowlers never learn'],
 array['Hip Drive with Full Run-Up','Resisted Hip Drive Sprint'],
 array['Standing Hip Extension','Glute Bridge Hip Drive'],
 array['cricket','fast_bowling','hip_power','speed','sports_specific'],
 array['acute_lower_back_injury','hip_flexor_strain_acute'],
 'explosive', 'sagittal', true, 3, 12, null, 60, true),

('Cricket Batting Stance Stability',
 'quads', array['core','glutes','hip_flexors'], array['quads','core','glutes'],
 'sport_specific', 'isometric', array['bodyweight','resistance_bands'], 'beginner', false,
 'Hold the batting stance (feet shoulder-width, weight centered, slight crouch, hands in grip position) while a partner applies gentle pushes from different directions. Resist the perturbation while maintaining stance alignment. 30 seconds × 5 sets.',
 'Over-widening the stance to resist pushes (the training stance must reflect the match stance — an artificially wide stance creates false stability), bracing so hard that the reactive responses are lost.',
 'cricket',
 array['The batting stance is the foundation of every shot: an unstable stance creates inconsistent shot-making across long innings','Perturbation training: partner pushes from unexpected angles and times — this trains the neuromuscular reflexes for staying balanced on difficult pitches (uneven bounce, body-line bowling)','Soft knees: the slight knee bend in the batting stance is the spring-loaded position — locked knees cannot respond quickly to unexpected deliveries','Good batting stances look effortless: the stability is neuromuscular, not brute force — this training develops that automatic stability'],
 array['Batting Stance with Perturbed Ball Feed','Dynamic Batting Stance Stability'],
 array['Basic Stance Hold','Batting Stance Mirror Check'],
 array['cricket','batting','stability','balance','sports_specific'],
