('Cricket Fast Bowling Plyometric Circuit',
 'quads', array['glutes','calves','hamstrings','core'], array['quads','glutes','calves'],
 'sport_specific', 'explosive', array['bodyweight','plyometric_box'], 'advanced', true,
 'A 20-minute circuit: Bounding 4 × 20m → Depth Jumps 4 × 8 → Single-Leg Hop to Bound 3 × 8 each → Medicine Ball Slam 3 × 10 → Lateral Bounds 3 × 8 each. 90-second rest between sets. Performed in pre-season to build the power base for bowling.',
 'Performing this circuit in-season at full volume (plyometric circuits should be reduced in season when bowling loads are high — the combined stress can exceed recovery capacity), not building up from low to high volume over 6-8 weeks.',
 'cricket',
 array['Plyometrics and bowling load: monitor total weekly sprints + jumps + overs bowled in the same week — exceeding 200 ''contacts'' per week in pre-season is a risk factor for stress injury','Bound stride specific: the bounding drill develops the specific power of the bowling bound stride — this is the most cricket-specific plyometric exercise','Quality over quantity: fast bowling plyometrics must be performed with maximum intent — 8 high-quality bounds are more valuable than 20 fatigued bounds','Wicket-to-wicket fast bowling run-up generates approximately 6-8 ground contacts of significant force — this circuit develops those forces in a controlled environment'],
 array['Advanced Fast Bowling Power Circuit','Combined Plyometric and Bowling Program'],
 array['Simple Jump Squat Circuit','Light Plyometric Introduction'],
 array['cricket','fast_bowling','plyometrics','power','pre_season'],
