('Cricket Wicketkeeper Lateral Movement',
 'glutes', array['glute_medius','adductors','calves','quads'], array['glutes','glute_medius'],
 'sport_specific', 'locomotion', array['resistance_bands','agility_cones'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Place lateral resistance band around the ankles. From wicketkeeper squat, shuffle laterally 3 steps to the right (taking a diving catch position), recover to center squat, shuffle 3 steps left. Perform 10 full sequences with the band, then 5 without the band.',
 'Standing up out of the squat during the lateral movement (must maintain the low crouched position throughout — standing up is the compensation for insufficient glute medius strength), not completing the dive take at the end of each lateral movement.',
 'cricket',
 array['Low and wide: the wicketkeeper must stay low during lateral movements — the power comes from the hips, not from dipping then rising','The band overloads the lateral movement: training with the band then removing it creates a post-activation potentiation effect — movements feel faster without the band','Take simulation: the lateral shuffle ends with a glove take (hands simulate catching) — this integrates the hand-eye skill into the athletic conditioning drill','Test match wicketkeepers perform 400-800 lateral shuffles per day across a long day in the field — this endurance must be built systematically in pre-season'],
 array['Wicketkeeper Lateral with Ball Feed','Full Wicketkeeper Agility Circuit'],
 array['Lateral Shuffle Without Band','Simple Squat Hold'],
