('Cricket Batting Grip and Forearm Strength',
 'forearms', array['wrist_flexors','finger_flexors','biceps'], array['forearms'],
 'sport_specific', 'isolation', array['grip_trainer','dumbbells'], 'beginner', false,
 'A grip and forearm program for batters: 1) Plate pinch (2kg → 5kg) hold 30s × 5 each hand. 2) Fat grip dumbbell wrist curl 3 × 20. 3) Towel pull-up dead hang 3 × 20s. 4) Wrist roller 3 sets. Performed 3 times per week in pre-season.',
 'Training only wrist curls (the complete batting grip requires multiple forearm and finger muscle groups — a comprehensive program addresses all of them), neglecting the non-dominant hand (the top hand in batting typically controls the bat face angle).',
 'cricket',
 array['Top hand controls direction: the top hand (the one on the handle closer to the bat face) guides the angle of the bat — this hand''s forearm strength directly determines shot placement','Bottom hand provides power: the bottom hand generates the shot force at ball contact — both hands serve different functions and should be trained accordingly','The wrist roller is the most effective forearm tool: it trains wrist flexion, extension, supination, and pronation through full range in a single fatigue-building exercise','Grip strength and bat speed are correlated in cricket: a measured grip strength increase of 10% produces a measurable bat speed increase'],
 array['Heavy Grip Training With Bat Weight','Advanced Forearm and Grip Circuit'],
