('Cricket Fielding Slide Stop',
 'core', array['glutes','hip_flexors','shoulder','quads'], array['core','glutes','shoulder'],
 'sport_specific', 'explosive', array['bodyweight','yoga_mat'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Sprint 5m toward a ball position, perform a slide stop (drop to the non-dominant side, hands reaching for the ball), collect the simulated ball, rise to a throwing position, make an imaginary throw. Complete 6 reps each side.',
 'Stopping with the knees (knee-first sliding causes patellar and MCL injuries — the landing surfaces should be the side of the thigh and hip), not using the momentum of the sprint in the slide (the slide uses the running energy to cover extra ground).',
 'cricket',
 array['Hip and thigh landing: the correct slide contacts the floor with the thigh and hip simultaneously, not the knee','The slide extends the fielding range: a well-executed slide stop adds 1-2 metres of fielding reach compared to stopping on the feet','Both sides: cricket fielders develop preferred sides for sliding — training both sides prevents asymmetric compensation and injury patterns','The throw from the ground: rising from the slide to a throwing position quickly is a separate skill — practice the full sequence every rep'],
 array['Full-Speed Fielding Slide with Ball','Boundary Fielding Slide Circuit'],
 array['Slow Walk-Through Slide Technique','Controlled Dive onto Mat'],
 array['cricket','fielding','slide_stop','agility','sports_specific'],
