('Cricket Overhead Catch Jump',
 'calves', array['quads','glutes','shoulder','core'], array['calves','quads','shoulder'],
 'sport_specific', 'explosive', array['bodyweight','medicine_ball'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Set up near a wall or have a partner throw. Sprint 3 steps, jump off one foot, catch a ball thrown overhead at maximum height. Land on two feet and maintain balance. 6-8 catches each dominant foot take-off. Simulates catching a high ball from a spin bowler or drive.',
 'Jumping off two feet (in cricket, most catching jumps are one-footed — train the specific pattern), not looking the ball into the hands (eyes on the ball from the moment of sight to catch completion).',
 'cricket',
 array['One-footed jump: this develops the specific neuromuscular pattern of the cricket catching jump, which almost always launches from a running step-into-jump','Eyes on the ball: from the moment the ball is sighted, the gaze must not leave it until it is in the hands','Land balanced: the ability to land and hold position after the catch reflects the core and lower body control needed to execute accurately under fatigue','High catches are the highest pressure moments in cricket: players who have trained this exact movement pattern perform better under the pressure'],
 array['Overhead Catch Jump with Dive','Slip Catching Circuit'],
 array['Standing Overhead Catch Reach','Jump and Catch with Two-Foot Take-Off'],
 array['cricket','catching','explosive','vertical_jump','sports_specific'],
