('Cricket Change of Pace Speed Endurance',
 'quads', array['hamstrings','glutes','calves'], array['quads','hamstrings'],
 'sport_specific', 'locomotion', array['bodyweight'], 'advanced', true,
 'Fielding endurance circuit: 60% effort jog for 30 seconds → 100% sprint for 5 seconds → back to jog → 100% sprint for 5 seconds → back to jog → repeat for 6 minutes continuously. Simulates the demands of a full day of fielding with random sprint bursts.',
 'Jogging at too low an intensity (the jog must be 60-70% of max heart rate — walking between sprints is not representative of fielding demands), reducing the sprint intensity as fatigue builds (each sprint must be maximum effort regardless of fatigue).',
 'cricket',
 array['The game demands: a fielder in a one-day game sprints 20-30 times in a full day''s fielding, interspersed with jogging between positions and walking between overs','Variable sprint triggers: in the real game, sprints are triggered by unpredictable events — train with a partner who calls the sprint randomly rather than at set intervals','Heart rate monitoring: in this drill, the jog phase should prevent full recovery (HR stays above 65%) while allowing partial recovery before the next sprint — this is the metabolic demand of fielding','Building to 6 minutes: start with 3 minutes in pre-season and build to 6 minutes over 6-8 weeks'],
 array['6-Minute Fielding Endurance Full Speed','Competition-Day Fielding Simulation'],
 array['3-Minute Fielding Endurance','Simple Interval Sprint Training'],
 array['cricket','fielding','endurance','speed','pre_season'],
