('Cricket Batting Upper Body Strength',
 'lats', array['biceps','forearms','core','deltoids'], array['lats','biceps','core'],
 'sport_specific', 'pull', array['barbell','dumbbells','cable_machine'], 'intermediate', true,
 'A batting-specific upper body strength program: Barbell Row 4 × 6 (pulling strength of the batting stroke) → Cable Rotation 3 × 12 each side → Single-Arm Row 3 × 10 each → Wrist Curl 3 × 20 → Reverse Wrist Curl 3 × 20. Performed 2× per week in pre-season.',
 'Overloading the pressing muscles (cricket batting is a pull-dominant movement — the power of the batting stroke comes from pulling the handle through the ball with the top hand. Too much chest pressing creates imbalances that reduce bat control).',
 'cricket',
 array['Batting is a pulling pattern: the top hand pulls the bat handle through the ball at contact — this is a lat and bicep dominated action, not a pushing action','The row to batting translation: the barbell row develops the pulling strength that directly translates to harder driving through the ball','2:1 pull to push ratio: cricket batters should train twice as much pulling as pushing to develop cricket-specific strength and prevent the shoulder imbalances that cause rotator cuff injuries','Bilateral balance: the batting action is strongly asymmetric — train both sides of the body equally in the gym to prevent the long-term postural adaptations of one-sided sport'],
 array['Bat Speed Training with Resistance','Advanced Cricket-Specific Upper Body'],
 array['Simple Dumbbell Row','Band Pull Training'],
 array['cricket','batting','upper_body_strength','lat','sports_specific'],
 array['shoulder_injuries_acute','elbow_injuries_acute'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', false, 4, 8, null, 90, true),

('Cricket T20 Explosive Batting Power',
 'glutes', array['quads','core','deltoids','forearms'], array['glutes','quads','core'],
 'sport_specific', 'explosive', array['medicine_ball','resistance_bands'], 'advanced', true,
 'Power circuit for T20 batting: Broad Jump × 6 (generating ground force) → Medicine Ball Overhead Slam × 8 → Jump Squat × 6 → Rotational Medicine Ball Throw × 10 each side → Banded Bat Swing × 12 each side. Rest 2 minutes between 4 sets.',
 'Treating this as a strength circuit (must be performed with maximum explosive intent — partial effort produces partial power, not strength), not recovering between sets (power exercises require full recovery to maintain maximal output).',
 'cricket',
 array['Intent is the signal: each rep must be performed with 100% power intent. The nervous system responds to maximum effort signals by increasing fast-twitch fiber recruitment.','The jump squat translates to batting: the explosive hip extension in the jump squat is identical to the power generation in the T20 slog — training one improves the other','T20 batting requires explosive power for clearing the boundary: the most effective power training combines vertical (jumping), rotational (med ball), and sport-specific (banded bat swing) exercises','Peak power in T20 batting: a six over the boundary requires approximately 40-50 watts more power than a defensive shot — this circuit develops exactly that additional power'],
 array['Loaded T20 Power Circuit','Competition-Pace Power Batting Drill'],
 array['Medicine Ball Rotation Only','Box Jump Introduction'],
 array['cricket','T20','batting_power','explosive','sports_specific'],
 array['acute_lower_back_injury','knee_injuries_acute','shoulder_injuries'],
