('Cricket Spin Bowling Hip Mobility',
 'hip_flexors', array['groin','piriformis','IT_band'], array['hip_flexors','groin'],
 'sport_specific', 'stretch', array['yoga_mat'], 'beginner', false,
 'Spin bowling requires extreme hip external rotation for the bowling arm side. Daily mobility work: Hip 90/90 × 2min each → Pigeon Pose × 2min each → Hip External Rotation CARs × 10 each → Seated Cross-Leg Forward Fold × 90s. Perform daily during bowling periods.',
 'Only stretching one side (spin bowlers have dramatically different hip mobility between sides from years of asymmetric loading — both sides require equal attention to prevent pelvic and lower back compensation patterns).',
 'cricket',
 array['The spin bowler''s hip: the hip of the bowling arm side must externally rotate fully at the moment of ball release — restricted hip external rotation forces the spine to compensate, directly causing lumbar injury','Daily mobility: during the competition season, spin bowlers should perform this hip sequence daily — the bowling action reinforces hip restriction, not flexibility','The 90/90 stretch is the most effective single exercise for a spin bowler''s hip: it targets the anterior AND posterior hip capsule in one position','Left-arm spin note: left-arm orthodox and left-arm wrist-spin (chinaman) have different hip demands to their right-arm counterparts — consider individual screening'],
 array['Advanced Hip External Rotation Work','Full Spin Bowling Mobility Protocol'],
 array['Simple Hip Flexor Lunge','Gentle Seated Hip Stretch'],
 array['cricket','spin_bowling','hip_mobility','injury_prevention','flexibility'],
 array['hip_replacement','acute_hip_injuries','SI_joint_instability_severe'],
 'isometric', 'multi', false, 1, null, 600, null, true),

('Cricket Long-Tail Batting Concentration',
 'core', array['hip_flexors','quads'], array['core','hip_flexors'],
 'sport_specific', 'isometric', array['bodyweight'], 'intermediate', false,
 'A mental toughness and physical endurance drill: Hold the batting stance for 3 minutes continuously (simulating the physical demands of a long innings). Breathe steadily. Maintain mental focus on an imaginary ball trajectory. Repeat 3-5 times with 2-minute walking recovery.',
 'Widening the stance or leaning on the bat during the hold (must maintain the exact match stance without props), losing mental focus (the drill is as much about concentration training as physical endurance).',
 'cricket',
 array['The test of batting endurance: during a long innings, a batter stands in the crease for hundreds of deliveries — the physical and mental fatigue of maintaining the batting stance is rarely trained','Breathing pattern: maintain a relaxed, rhythmic breathing pattern throughout the hold — breath-holding during the hold recreates the muscular tension pattern that causes poor shot selection when fatigued','Mental imagery: during the hold, visualize actual deliveries being bowled and mentally play each shot — this combines physical endurance with the cognitive demands of batting','3 minutes × 3 sets simulates the demands of approximately a 45-minute batting spell in terms of stance-time — adjust for specific formats (T20 vs Test match)'],
 array['4-Minute Batting Stance Hold','Full Batting Concentration Session'],
 array['1-Minute Batting Stance Hold','Simple Batting Stance Practice'],
 array['cricket','batting','endurance','concentration','mental_toughness'],
