('AFL Mark Jump (Vertical Leap Training)',
 'quads', array['glutes','calves','hamstrings','core'], array['quads','glutes','calves'],
 'sport_specific', 'explosive', array['bodyweight','plyometric_box'], 'advanced', true,
 'Sprint 3-5 steps and jump from one foot (the mark is typically taken off one foot in AFL). Reach maximum height with both hands raised in a catching position. Land on two feet, balance, and hold the catch position 1 second before returning. 8 reps each foot.',
 'Jumping from two feet (AFL marks are almost always taken from a running one-footed jump — the one-foot take-off generates more height through horizontal velocity conversion), not practicing both feet equally.',
 'AFL',
 array['Velocity to height: the running approach converts horizontal speed to vertical lift — the faster the approach, the higher the potential jump (within technical limits)','The penultimate step: the step before the take-off foot is a longer, lower step that loads the glute and calves for the explosive jump','Both hands up: AFL marking technique requires both hands reaching simultaneously — the catch position is hands slightly above and in front of the face','Train the mark under fatigue: a player who can mark cleanly after a 60m sprint is more valuable than one who can only mark from stationary'],
 array['Contested Mark Training','Mark Jump Over a Player'],
 array['Standing Jump to Catch','Box Jump'],
 array['AFL','marking','vertical_jump','explosive','sports_specific'],
 array['knee_injuries_acute','ankle_injuries_acute'],
 'explosive', 'sagittal', true, 4, 8, null, 90, true),

('AFL Repeated Sprint Ability Test',
 'quads', array['hamstrings','glutes','calves'], array['quads','hamstrings'],
 'sport_specific', 'locomotion', array['bodyweight'], 'advanced', true,
 'The AFL RSA (Repeated Sprint Ability) Protocol: 6 × 30m sprints with only 20-second recovery between sprints. Record time for each sprint. The % drop-off in time from sprint 1 to sprint 6 is the RSA score (less drop-off = better).',
 'Full recovery between sprints (the 20-second recovery is deliberately insufficient — the incomplete recovery is the testing variable), not recording times for each sprint (the sprint times track fatigue profile).',
 'AFL',
 array['20-second recovery is intentionally short: the incomplete recovery creates the oxygen debt that replicates match conditions in the final quarter','RSA performance: the best AFL players show less than 5% speed reduction from sprint 1 to sprint 6 — this is the elite standard','This test also functions as a conditioning drill: regular practice improves RSA as the body adapts to the repeated sprint demand','AFL match analysis: field players perform 40-80 high-intensity sprints per game with very short recovery windows — RSA is the most match-specific conditioning capacity to develop'],
 array['RSA with Change of Direction','AFL-Specific Repeated Sprint Protocol'],
 array['3 × 30m Sprints with Full Recovery','Acceleration Drill 20m'],
 array['AFL','speed','repeated_sprint','conditioning','sports_specific'],
 array['hamstring_strain_recent','stress_fractures_lower_limb','cardiovascular_conditions'],
 'explosive', 'sagittal', false, 2, 6, null, 20, true),

('AFL Overhead Ball Handball',
 'deltoids', array['triceps','core','hip_flexors'], array['deltoids','core'],
 'sport_specific', 'explosive', array['football_AFL'], 'beginner', true,
 'The AFL handball — punching the ball from the non-preferred hand — must be practiced at speed and varying distances. Set up target circles at 5m, 10m, 15m. Perform 20 handballs to each target distance from a standing position and then while running.',
 'Handballing with the preferred hand (the non-preferred hand holds and guides — the dominant hand punches. This is often confused by beginners), not following through toward the target (the arm swing through toward the target is the accuracy mechanism).',
 'AFL',
 array['Hold and guide with the non-preferred hand: the ball rests in the non-preferred palm, and the preferred hand punches through it','The fist: the ball must be hit with a clenched fist, specifically the meat of the hand — not the knuckles, not an open palm','Follow-through to the target: the punching arm should end up pointing directly at the intended target — the follow-through generates accuracy','Handball accuracy under pressure: in match conditions, handballs are executed while being tackled, sprinting, or changing direction — train from moving positions'],
 array['Handball While Running at Speed','Handball Under Tackle Pressure'],
 array['Standing Handball Practice','Slow Handball Technique'],
 array['AFL','handball','skills','accuracy','sports_specific'],
 array['wrist_injuries_acute','finger_injuries'],
 'push', 'sagittal', true, 3, 20, null, 30, true),

('Rugby Tackle Bag Circuit',
 'quads', array['glutes','hamstrings','core','shoulders'], array['quads','glutes','core'],
 'sport_specific', 'explosive', array['tackle_bag','shield'], 'advanced', true,
 'Set up 3 tackle bags. Sprint 5m into tackle bag 1 (shoulder height contact, drive forward 3m), reset, sprint 5m to bag 2, reset, sprint to bag 3. Rest 2 minutes. Perform 6 sets. Focus on low body position, leg drive, and safe contact technique.',
 'Leading with the head in the tackle (the head must go to the SIDE of the ball carrier, never directly in front — head-on tackles cause catastrophic cervical spine injuries), tackling without leg drive (the tackle is a leg exercise: short fast strides after contact drive the carrier backward).',
 'rugby',
 array['Head to the side: the golden rule of tackling — the tackler''s head goes to the side of the ball carrier''s body. No exceptions.','Low body position: get low before contact, not after — once contact is made, it is too late to lower the hips','Leg drive after contact: the tackle does not end at contact. Short, fast strides after the shoulder makes contact drives the carrier backward.','This is one of the highest-impact exercises in sport — never perform it without proper technique foundations and always use appropriate protective equipment'],
 array['Full Speed Tackle Circuit','Tackle Bag Combination Drill'],
 array['Stationary Tackle Bag Push','Tackle Technique on Stationary Partner'],
 array['rugby','tackling','contact','explosive','sports_specific'],
 array['neck_injuries','shoulder_injuries_acute','concussion_protocol_recent'],
 'explosive', 'sagittal', false, 6, 3, null, 120, true),

('AFL Kick Power Training',
 'quads', array['glutes','hip_flexors','calves','core'], array['quads','glutes','hip_flexors'],
 'sport_specific', 'explosive', array['bodyweight','resistance_bands'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Kicking power circuit: Hip Flexor Lunge with High Knee Drive × 10 each → Single-Leg Romanian Deadlift (kicking leg swing control) × 12 each → Band-Resisted Hip Flexion Kick × 15 each → Bounding (long, powerful strides) × 4 × 30m. Performed twice weekly.',
 'Training only the quadriceps (AFL kicking is a full kinetic chain movement: glutes → hip flexors → quads → calves → foot. Quad-only training produces stronger but not faster kicks), neglecting the standing leg (the standing leg generates the stable base from which kicking power is expressed).',
 'AFL',
 array['The kinetic chain of kicking: ground force through the standing leg → hip extension → hip flexion of kicking leg → knee extension → plantar flexion at ball contact — each link must be strong and sequenced correctly','Hip flexion speed determines kicking distance: the angular velocity of hip flexion (bringing the thigh toward the torso) is the primary driver of kicking power, not quad strength alone','Bounding develops kicking: the bounding exercise develops the explosive hip extension-to-hip flexion pattern that is exactly replicated in the kicking action','The standing leg: add single-leg stability work (single-leg squat, single-leg RDL) to develop the platform from which powerful kicks originate'],
 array['Resisted Kick Training','Full-Speed Kicking with Distance Measurement'],
 array['Simple High Knee March','Standing Hip Flexion with Band'],
 array['AFL','kicking','power','hip_flexor','sports_specific'],
 array['hip_flexor_strain_acute','knee_injuries_acute','groin_injuries'],
 'explosive', 'sagittal', true, 3, 12, null, 60, true),

('Rugby Scrum Leg Drive',
 'quads', array['glutes','hamstrings','core','erectors'], array['quads','glutes','erectors'],
 'sport_specific', 'push', array['scrum_machine','bodyweight'], 'advanced', true,
 'Position in a scrum body position (low hips, flat back, head up, bind on a scrum machine or wall). Drive forward with both legs simultaneously, maintaining the low body position. Drive for 3 seconds, reset, drive again. 3 × 8 drives with 2-minute rest.',
 'Rising out of the scrum body position during the drive (the hips must stay low — if the hips rise, the drive force becomes upward rather than forward, pushing the opponent into the machine rather than backward), binding too loosely on the machine.',
 'rugby',
 array['The scrum body position: flat back parallel to the floor, hips lower than the shoulders — this is the most mechanically advantageous pushing position','Drive direction is horizontal: if the shoulders rise above the hips during the drive, the force vector angles upward — horizontal force wins scrum contests, not vertical','Foot placement: feet should be wide and slightly staggered — this creates a stable base and allows maximum horizontal force generation','The 8-man bind: in a real scrum, all 8 players must coordinate their drive timing — this individual drill builds the personal technique that team coordination requires'],
 array['Scrum Machine Circuit','Competition Scrum Simulation'],
 array['Wall Drive Technique','Prowler Push'],
 array['rugby','scrum','leg_drive','technique','sports_specific'],
 array['neck_injuries','shoulder_injuries_acute','acute_lower_back_injury'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 3, 8, null, 120, true),

('AFL Sprint Position-Specific Acceleration',
 'quads', array['hamstrings','glutes','calves'], array['quads','hamstrings'],
 'sport_specific', 'explosive', array['bodyweight','agility_cones'], 'advanced', true,
 'Position-specific sprint drill: set up a 30m course. Midfielder drill: sprint 10m → decelerate → change direction → sprint 10m → decelerate → sprint 10m. This replicates the midfielder''s repeated acceleration pattern. Record each segment time.',
 'Sprinting at the same speed in each segment (match play involves varying intensities — the conditioning drill should replicate this variation), not including the deceleration (decelerating quickly is as important as accelerating quickly and is often undertrained).',
 'AFL',
 array['Deceleration as training: the ability to decelerate quickly (in 3-4 steps from full speed) is as important as acceleration in AFL — it is trained specifically in this drill','Position-specificity: midfielders repeat this pattern 80-100 times per game. Forwards have longer, fewer sprints. Backmen have reactive sprints. Tailor the drill to the position.','Change of direction angle: the 45° and 90° direction changes are most common in AFL. Train these angles specifically rather than random or unrealistic 180° turns.','The 30m limit: AFL sprint efforts rarely exceed 40m. Most are 10-25m. Training predominantly at match-relevant distances is more specific than 100m speed work.'],
 array['Position-Specific Sprint with Decision-Making','Game-Speed Sprint Circuit AFL'],
 array['Simple Acceleration Drill','Cone Sprint Pattern Basic'],
 array['AFL','acceleration','position_specific','speed','sports_specific'],
 array['hamstring_strain_recent','ankle_injuries_acute'],
 'explosive', 'multi', false, 5, 3, null, 120, true),

('Rugby Lineout Jump Training',
 'calves', array['quads','glutes','shoulders','core'], array['calves','quads','glutes'],
 'sport_specific', 'explosive', array['bodyweight','plyometric_box'], 'advanced', true,
 'Practice the lineout jump: from a standing position, jump off two feet reaching both hands maximally overhead. Progress to: jumper holding a ball overhead and maintaining it while two lifters raise them. Practice the lift-and-hold position for 3 seconds × 8 reps.',
 'Not working with lifters in training (the jump mechanics change significantly when supported by lifters — the lifter-supported jump reaches 4-6m, far beyond what unassisted jumping can develop), jumping before the timing signal.',
 'rugby',
 array['The lineout jump is a team skill: the jumper, lifter 1, and lifter 2 must coordinate their timing to get maximum height at the moment of ball arrival','Timing the jump: the jumper initiates the jump slightly before the throw arrives — the peak jump height must coincide with the ball being catchable','Body tension in the lift: when lifted, the jumper must maintain a straight, rigid body position — a collapsed body position is both harder for lifters and reduces the reaching height','The ball presentation: catching the ball at maximum height is only half the skill — presenting it cleanly to the scrumhalf while supported by lifters requires practice under fatigue'],
 array['Full Lineout Practice with Throw','Lineout Competition Simulation'],
 array['Vertical Jump Practice','Standing Reach Jump'],
 array['rugby','lineout','vertical_jump','teamwork','sports_specific'],
 array['shoulder_injuries_acute','knee_injuries_acute'],
 'explosive', 'sagittal', false, 4, 8, null, 60, true),

('AFL Contested Ball Ruck Work',
 'core', array['glutes','quads','deltoids','triceps'], array['core','glutes','deltoids'],
 'sport_specific', 'explosive', array['bodyweight','medicine_ball'], 'advanced', true,
 'Simulate the ruck contest: face a partner holding a medicine ball between you at head height. On signal, both players jump and compete for the ball with a sweeping arm motion. Perform the ruck tap (batting the ball to a teammate position). 5 reps each direction.',
 'Jumping early before the ball position is set (ruck timing is the elite skill — jumping half a second early means hitting the ball at a declining trajectory, not at peak height), using the wrist to tap instead of the whole arm sweep.',
 'AFL',
 array['The ruck tap: the ball is swept with the full arm in a controlled arc — the wrist does not flex. Think of sweeping a ball off a shelf with a straight arm.','Timing from the umpire signal: in AFL, the ruck contest begins from the umpire''s bounce — the ruckman must read the bounce angle and time their jump accordingly','Direct the tap: the tap must go to a specific teammate position — random tapping loses 40-50% of ruck contests immediately','Ruck fitness: AFL ruckmen contest 30-60 ruck contests per game across 4 quarters. Each contest involves a sprint, a jump, and often physical contact — the combined energy demand is enormous'],
 array['Full Ruck Contest with Directional Tap','Ruck Contest Under Fatigue'],
 array['Standing Arm Reach','Vertical Jump Practice'],
 array['AFL','rucking','contested_ball','vertical_jump','sports_specific'],
 array['shoulder_injuries_acute','concussion_protocol_recent'],
 'explosive', 'multi', false, 4, 5, null, 60, true),

('Rugby Breakdown Strength',
 'core', array['glutes','quads','erectors','deltoids'], array['core','glutes','erectors'],
 'sport_specific', 'isometric', array['bodyweight','resistance_bands'], 'advanced', true,
 'Simulate the breakdown body position (low hips, flat back, feet wide, one hand on the ground for support). Hold this position against partner resistance (partner tries to push the player off the ball). 5 seconds maximum resistance. 8 reps.',
 'Not achieving the correct body position before applying force (breakdown technique must be set correctly — arms straight, hips below shoulders, head up), competing against the ground rather than against the opponent (the breakdown is a pushing contest against a human, not a static floor).',
 'rugby',
 array['Body position: the breakdown requires the hip below the shoulder plane, feet wide and behind the hips, head up — this is the mechanically strongest position','The ruck body position is the same as the scrum body position: hip extension strength, lower back strength, and horizontal force generation are the same capacities','Counter-ruck: the ability to dislodge an opponent from the breakdown requires a rapid acceleration from a crouched position — similar to a low-start sprint','Penalty risk: in rugby, illegal breakdown technique (holding on, wrong body position) is the most common source of penalties — coaching the exact technique in training reduces this'],
 array['Breakdown Circuit with Multiple Contests','Ruck Machine Work'],
 array['Breakdown Body Position Hold','Wall Push in Breakdown Position'],
 array['rugby','breakdown','ruck','contact','sports_specific'],
 array['neck_injuries','shoulder_injuries_acute','acute_lower_back_injury'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 4, 8, null, 60, true),

('AFL Vertical Power for Contested Marking',
 'quads', array['glutes','calves','core','deltoids'], array['quads','glutes','calves'],
 'sport_specific', 'explosive', array['bodyweight','resistance_bands'], 'advanced', true,
 'Contested marking power circuit: Depth Jump from 40cm box × 6 → Jump with arm fight (simulate using arms against a partner) × 8 → Single-Leg Jump to two-foot land × 6 each → Standing Broad Jump × 6. Rest 2 minutes between 4 sets.',
 'Performing depth jumps with a box too high (contact time with the ground is the variable to develop — the box height is a tool, not a goal. 40cm is optimal for most athletes).',
 'AFL',
 array['Depth jump mechanics: step off the box, do not jump off — the goal is minimum ground contact time after landing, maximum jump height. ''Touch the ground and leave it'' is the cue.','Arms in contested marks: the most elite contest-markers use their arms to create space and deflect opponents — the arm fight is a separate skill that must be practiced under jump conditions','Single-leg jump to two-foot land: the AFL mark is often taken by jumping off one foot and landing safely on two — this specific pattern reduces ankle and knee landing injury risk','Contested marking is the most crowd-pleasing skill in AFL: the training for it is also one of the most explosive and athletically demanding in team sport'],
 array['Heavy Contested Marking Circuit','Mark Practice at Full Game Speed'],
 array['Box Jump Standard','Standing Vertical Jump Test'],
 array['AFL','contested_marking','plyometrics','explosive','vertical_power'],
 array['knee_injuries_acute','ankle_injuries_acute'],
 'explosive', 'sagittal', false, 4, 6, null, 120, true),

('Rugby Neck Strengthening Protocol',
 'neck', array['upper_trapezius','SCM','erectors'], array['neck','upper_trapezius'],
 'sport_specific', 'isometric', array['resistance_bands','bodyweight'], 'intermediate', false,
 'A rugby-specific neck strengthening circuit (mandatory for all contact players): 1) Neck flexion isometric 3 × 10s each direction. 2) Partner neck resistance all 4 directions 3 × 10 reps. 3) Neck bridge on mat (advanced) 3 × 20s. 4) Shrugs 3 × 15. Perform 3× per week.',
 'Skipping this program (neck strength is the primary modifiable risk factor for concussion and cervical spine injury in contact sports — this program is not optional for rugby players), using too much resistance on the isometric holds (the neck musculature is smaller than most gym exercises — start conservative).',
 'rugby',
 array['Neck strength is concussion protection: research shows that players with greater neck strength have lower rates of concussion — the neck muscles absorb the impact forces before they reach the brain','All four directions: flex (forward), extend (backward), lateral flex (side) — all four must be trained equally. Imbalanced neck strength is its own risk factor.','The neck bridge: an advanced exercise from wrestling — only attempt with coaching supervision. The neck must be strong before performing a full neck bridge.','Position-specific emphasis: loosies and halfbacks take more head-on tackles — they need more flexion strength. Locks and tighthead props need more extension strength for scrummaging.'],
 array['Heavy Neck Resistance Program','Advanced Neck Bridge Variations'],
 array['Gentle Neck Isometrics Only','Simple Neck Stability'],
 array['rugby','neck_strength','concussion_prevention','contact','injury_prevention'],
 array['cervical_injuries_history','acute_neck_injuries','cervical_stenosis'],
 'isometric', 'multi', false, 3, 10, null, 30, true),

('AFL Agility: T-Drill Modified',
 'quads', array['calves','glutes','hamstrings'], array['quads','calves','glutes'],
 'sport_specific', 'locomotion', array['agility_cones'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Set cones in an AFL-T pattern: a 40m straight, with cones at 10m intervals. Sprint to the first cone, sidestep to the second cone (5m either side), sprint through to the third cone, sidestep back, sprint to the fourth cone, agility shuffle to the end. Record time for each complete pattern.',
 'Rounding the cones (must touch each cone — cutting corners changes the body angles and removes the deceleration-reacceleration demands that the drill develops), crossing feet during the lateral shuffle (slide step only — feet should never cross).',
 'AFL',
 array['Touch the cone: reaching down and touching the cone forces complete deceleration at each change point — rushing past the cone trains the wrong habit','Slide step in the shuffle: feet never cross — maintaining the slide step (like a defensive slide in basketball) keeps the hips square and the weight centered for explosive redirection','The bottom shuffle direction: the lateral shuffle at the bottom of the T trains the cut-and-accelerate pattern used when a flanker changes direction to create separation','AFL agility ranking: the T-drill time is one of the key measures at AFL Draft Combines — elite times are sub-9.5 seconds for the full AFL T-drill'],
 array['AFL T-Drill at Full Speed','AFL T-Drill with Ball'],
 array['Basic Agility Ladder','Simple Cone Drill'],
 array['AFL','agility','change_of_direction','speed','sports_specific'],
