('Rugby Pass Stability and Core',
 'obliques', array['deltoids','core','wrists','forearms'], array['obliques','deltoids','core'],
 'sport_specific', 'rotation', array['rugby_ball','resistance_bands'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Rugby passing stability circuit: Seated medicine ball throw (both sides of the body) × 15 → Standing cable push-pass simulation × 15 each → Split-stance rotational throw × 12 each → Push-up position plank with arm reach × 15 each. This develops passing power, shoulder stability, and core.',
 'Throwing with the arms only (rugby passing is a torso rotation-driven movement — the same hip rotation principles as cricket batting apply), not training both sides (rugby players pass predominantly to one side — training both sides corrects the asymmetric strength development).',
 'rugby',
 array['Torso rotation drives the pass: the non-throwing shoulder rotates away as the throwing shoulder drives through — this is a hip and core movement, not an arm movement','Both sides equally: rugby players who can pass only to their strong side are a tactical liability — ambidextrous passing is the mark of an elite rugby player','The spin on the ball comes from the trailing hand: the non-dominant hand is the spin generator — practice the wrist release of both hands separately','Passing under fatigue: rugby passes are made in the 75th-80th minute with full-match fatigue — train this skill in the later stages of conditioning sessions, not only when fresh'],
 array['Rugby Pass Under Tackle Pressure','Speed Pass Circuit'],
 array['Seated Medicine Ball Pass','Simple Rotational Throw'],
 array['rugby','passing','core_rotation','upper_body','sports_specific'],
 array['shoulder_injuries_acute','wrist_injuries_acute','elbow_injuries'],
 'mixed', 'transverse', false, 3, 15, null, 45, true),

('AFL Pre-Season Running Block',
 'quads', array['hamstrings','glutes','calves','hip_flexors'], array['quads','hamstrings','glutes'],
 'sport_specific', 'locomotion', array['bodyweight'], 'advanced', true,
 'An AFL pre-season aerobic base session: 20-minute continuous aerobic run (70% max HR) → 6 × 400m at threshold pace (2-minute recovery between) → 10-minute aerobic cool-down. Total: approximately 45-50 minutes. Progress to 3 sessions per week in pre-season.',
 'Running every session at high intensity (the aerobic base run must be genuinely easy — the threshold intervals provide the high-intensity stimulus, the aerobic runs provide the base — both are required).',
 'AFL',
 array['AFL match demands: field players cover 12-15km per game at varying intensities. A high aerobic base supports the repeated sprint ability and recovery between efforts.','The 400m at threshold: AFL players need a strong lactate threshold for sustained high-tempo play. 400m repeats at HM pace (approximately 85% max HR) develop this specifically.','GPS monitoring in AFL: elite clubs use GPS to monitor running distances, sprint counts, and acceleration loads in pre-season — the total volume must be progressed systematically','The Yo-Yo Intermittent Recovery Test (Yo-Yo IR2) is the AFL Combine test for aerobic capacity — this training session directly improves Yo-Yo scores'],
 array['AFL Pre-Season Full Program','Match Simulation Running Week'],
 array['Easy Aerobic Run Only','Short AFL Running Introduction'],
 array['AFL','pre_season','aerobic_base','running','conditioning'],
 array['cardiovascular_conditions','stress_fractures_lower_limb'],
 'locomotion', 'sagittal', false, 1, null, 2700, null, true),

('Rugby Maul and Driving Leg Strength',
 'glutes', array['quads','erectors','hamstrings','core'], array['glutes','quads','erectors'],
 'sport_specific', 'push', array['bodyweight','sled'], 'advanced', true,
 'Sled push at the low angle used in mauls (approximately 30° forward lean). Drive for 10m maximum effort. Reset and repeat for 6 drives with 2-minute recovery. The forward lean angle and step pattern should replicate the maul body position.',
 'Pushing at a fully upright position (the maul requires a forward lean — the horizontal force component wins maul contests, not vertical force), allowing the hips to rise during the drive.',
 'rugby',
 array['30° forward lean: the sled push body angle should replicate the maul body position — this makes the strength training directly transferable to the game skill','Step pattern in the maul: short, fast, powerful steps generate more driving force than long strides — this is counterintuitive but biomechanically superior','The maul as a weapon: teams with strong maul capacity convert 60-70% of their mauls into tries. This exercise directly builds that match-winning capacity.','Binding in the maul: grip strength and arm strength are limiting factors in maul binding — include forearm and grip training alongside this exercise'],
 array['Heavy Sled Maul Simulation','Contact Maul Drive'],
 array['Light Sled Push','Prowler Push Upright'],
 array['rugby','maul','leg_drive','contact','sports_specific'],
 array['acute_lower_back_injury','shoulder_injuries_acute','knee_injuries_acute'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 4, 6, null, 120, true),

('AFL Handball at Speed',
 'deltoids', array['triceps','core','wrists'], array['deltoids','triceps','core'],
 'sport_specific', 'explosive', array['football_AFL'], 'intermediate', true,
 'Handball accuracy at speed drill: Sprint 10m, receive a handball from a partner, immediately handball back to a target cone while continuing to sprint. The handball must be accurate (within 1m of the target) while at full sprint speed. 10 reps each arm.',
 'Slowing down to handball (the entire challenge is maintaining speed while handballing — slowing down removes the match-specific demand), looking at the target instead of ahead (the most skilled AFL players handball accurately without looking at the target — peripheral vision).',
 'AFL',
 array['Handball while sprinting: this is a dual-task skill — locomotion and fine motor control are in competition. Developing the skill in training makes it automatic in the game.','Target handball at speed: in a match, the handball recipient is a moving player — train with a moving target (partner runs alongside and receives) for greater realism','Both arms under fatigue: perform the drill in the last 10 minutes of a conditioning session — the fatigue accurately replicates fourth-quarter game demands','The handball is 70% of AFL scoring sequences: getting the handball skill right under pressure, fatigue, and at speed is fundamental to the game'],
 array['Handball at Sprint with Pressure','AFL Handball Circuit at Speed'],
 array['Standing Handball Practice','Walking Handball Technique'],
 array['AFL','handball','skill_under_pressure','speed','sports_specific'],
 array['wrist_injuries_acute','finger_injuries','shoulder_injuries'],
 'push', 'sagittal', true, 3, 10, null, 45, true),

('Rugby Lineout Throw Accuracy',
 'deltoids', array['triceps','wrists','core'], array['deltoids','triceps','core'],
 'sport_specific', 'push', array['rugby_ball'], 'advanced', true,
 'The lineout throw must be accurate to a precise height and landing zone. Drill: mark a target on a wall at 4m height (lineout jumper''s hands at lift height). Throw 20 balls to the target at distances of 8m, 15m, and 22m. Record accuracy (hits/20).',
 'Throwing to static targets only (in a real lineout, the jumper is moving — practice with a moving target that replicates the lift trajectory), not practicing under match-replication conditions (noise, fatigue, pressure).',
 'rugby',
 array['Throw to where the hands will be: the hooker throws to the anticipated position of the jumper''s hands at peak lift height — this requires anticipating the lift trajectory','Throw consistency: elite lineout throwers achieve 95%+ accuracy. Any throw percentage below 85% means the opposition will target the lineout.','The throw mechanics: low hand releases the ball last, providing the spin. The high hand guides the direction. Both hands must release in the same plane.','Wind: lineout throwing accuracy is severely affected by cross-wind — practice in varied wind conditions and develop compensatory technique adjustments'],
 array['Lineout Throw Under Pressure','Competition Lineout Simulation'],
 array['Short Distance Throw Practice','Wall Target Throw'],
 array['rugby','lineout','throwing','accuracy','sports_specific'],
 array['shoulder_injuries_acute','elbow_injuries_acute','wrist_injuries'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 3, 20, null, 60, true),

('AFL Tackling Technique',
 'core', array['glutes','shoulder','quads'], array['core','glutes','shoulder'],
 'sport_specific', 'explosive', array['bodyweight','tackle_dummy'], 'intermediate', true,
 'AFL tackling drill: from a pursuit angle, make contact with a tackle dummy at hip height, wrapping both arms around the torso. Hold the tackle position 2 seconds, release, reset. Progress to tackling a moving partner at slow speed with protective equipment.',
 'Diving at the legs (AFL tackles are at the hip-to-waist zone — below the hips is a late and dangerous tackle, above the shoulders is illegal), not wrapping both arms (a single-arm tackle attempt is high-risk and often ineffective in stopping a player).',
 'AFL',
 array['Hip height contact: the tackle zone in AFL is between the hips and shoulders — aiming for the hips is the most controlled and effective contact point','Wrap both arms: the tackle is not complete until both arms are secured around the ball carrier — one-arm attempts allow the carrier to shake off and continue','Low body position before contact: get hips low before the contact point — players who are high at contact get driven backward by the momentum of the ball carrier','The AFL tackle is a contest: the ball carrier has protective rights, the tackler has dispossession rights — understanding the rules makes training more specific'],
 array['Tackle Technique at Speed with Moving Partner','Tackle Circuit with Multiple Opponents'],
 array['Tackle Dummy Contact Only','Stationary Tackle Hold'],
 array['AFL','tackling','contact','technique','sports_specific'],
